  "cards": [
   {
    "key": "1_1_g0",
    "front": "What are the two branches of the immune system?",
    "back": "Innate and adaptive (acquired)."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_1_g1",
    "front": "What are the two activities of any immune response, in order?",
    "back": "1) Recognition of non-self (self/non-self discrimination), then 2) effector mechanisms that contain and remove the threat."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_1_g2",
    "front": "What are the two failure modes of self/non-self discrimination?",
    "back": "Failure to recognize non-self -> infection; reaction against self -> autoimmunity."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_1_g3",
    "front": "What does 'layering/redundancy' mean in immunity?",
    "back": "Within each branch there are multiple overlapping means of protection (barriers, enzymes), effector mechanisms (phagocytosis, ADCC, complement), and components (cells, molecules, organs) so something can respond wherever a pathogen lands."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_1_g4",
    "front": "Name the purposes of the immune system.",
    "back": "Prevent and control infections, eliminate pathogens and their products, and tumor surveillance (with immunopathology -- hypersensitivity, autoimmunity, transplant rejection -- as the flip side)."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_1_g5",
    "front": "Common trap: do the 'two branches' mean humoral vs cell-mediated?",
    "back": "No. The two branches are innate vs adaptive. Humoral vs cell-mediated is a split WITHIN the adaptive branch."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g0",
    "front": "What do PRRs recognize, and what is the answer they return?",
    "back": "PRRs recognize conserved PAMPs (LPS, teichoic acid, mannose). The answer is always generic -- 'bacterium/fungus/non-self,' never the species."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g1",
    "front": "Innate vs adaptive on three axes (specificity, speed, memory)?",
    "back": "Innate = non-specific, fast, no memory. Adaptive = specific, slow on first exposure (7-10 days) then fast on recall (2-3 days), with memory."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g2",
    "front": "Primary vs memory (anamnestic) adaptive response timing?",
    "back": "Primary response ~7-10 days; memory/anamnestic response ~2-3 days. Innate is faster still (already present)."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g3",
    "front": "What is clonal expansion and what two fates follow?",
    "back": "One antigen-specific naive lymphocyte proliferates into identical clones; these differentiate into effector cells (act now, terminal) and memory cells (persist, re-activatable)."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g4",
    "front": "Humoral vs cell-mediated immunity -- which pathogens?",
    "back": "Humoral (antibodies/plasma cells) = extracellular pathogens; cell-mediated (cytotoxic T cells) = intracellular pathogens."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g5",
    "front": "How does a cytotoxic T cell eliminate an intracellular virus?",
    "back": "It kills the infected HOST cell; the pathogen dies indirectly. The CTL does NOT kill the virus directly, and antibody cannot enter the cell."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_2_g6",
    "front": "Why is the influenza vaccine given annually?",
    "back": "Influenza undergoes antigenic drift, so previously acquired (specific) immunity no longer matches and the vaccine must be updated."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g0",
    "front": "On a first (naive) encounter, which branch responds first and why?",
    "back": "Innate -- it is already present and buys time, because the primary adaptive response needs ~7-10 days."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g1",
    "front": "Give the two main innate->adaptive regulatory mechanisms.",
    "back": "1) Complement proteins activate B cells / lower the B-cell activation threshold. 2) Innate-cell cytokines steer B/T differentiation and antibody isotype."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g2",
    "front": "Give the two main adaptive->innate regulatory mechanisms.",
    "back": "1) T-cell cytokines increase phagocyte (macrophage/neutrophil) activity and intracellular killing. 2) Antibodies opsonize pathogens, giving phagocytes 'handles' to engulf them."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g3",
    "front": "What actually causes flu symptoms (aches, fever, chills)?",
    "back": "The host's own cytokine/inflammatory response -- immunopathology, not direct viral tissue destruction."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g4",
    "front": "Why is fever beneficial (the refrigerator analogy)?",
    "back": "Pathogens replicate best near 37 C, so raising body temperature slows their replication -- like a fridge slows spoilage -- buying the adaptive response time."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_3_g5",
    "front": "What roles does inflammation play?",
    "back": "It is initiated by innate immunity and helps remove a pathogen, limit/contain its spread, and participate in tissue repair -- but it also causes immunopathology and can carry into the adaptive response."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g0",
    "front": "What is the single origin of all blood cells?",
    "back": "The pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell (HSC), which commits to lymphoid, myeloid, or erythroid lineages."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g1",
    "front": "What is the only difference between interstitial fluid and lymph?",
    "back": "Location -- the same fluid is called lymph once it drains into a lymphatic vessel."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g2",
    "front": "What do lymph nodes vs the spleen filter?",
    "back": "Lymph nodes filter tissue-derived lymph; the spleen filters blood."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g3",
    "front": "Where is the adaptive response to a finger-cut pathogen initiated?",
    "back": "In the nearest draining lymph node (for a finger, the axillary node) -- not at the wound. For blood-borne antigen, the spleen does this."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g4",
    "front": "Why is the lymph node called 'the lymphocyte bar'?",
    "back": "It is where B and T cells meet and interact (T-cell help activates B cells), launching the adaptive response."
   },
   {
    "key": "1_4_g5",
    "front": "Inside the node, what is the sequence that launches the adaptive response?",
    "back": "DCs capture antigen -> DCs present it to T cells -> T cells activate B cells -> activated B cells proliferate in the germinal center."
   }
  ]
